{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_aurora_ver02/data/sn86076142/00415627002/1914020701/0129.xml":{"full_text":"THE TOMOPAH DAILY BONANZA, TONOPAH. NEVADA, FEBRUARY 7, 1914.\nPAGE TWO\nTONOPAH DAILY BONANZA\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF NYE OOUNTT.\nPubllaatd evarr vealBg. Sunday excepted, bjr the Tonopah Boudu Printing Co.,\nIncorporates.\nW. W. BOOTH. EDITOR AND MANAGER\nMEMBER NEVADA PRESS ASSOCIATION.\nOne Tear\nNine Montae\nSti Months\nof senerrletlee Mall far Uallr Boi\nIll 00 Three Mont he\nIll One Month\nI H One Week\nDelivered ay Carrier, 1.M Pe M.ata.\n.11.00\n1.00\nJO\n11 REWARD.\nA reward of II will be paid for Information that will lead to the arreat\nand conviction of partlea stealing The Bonanza from eubacrlbera.\nTO SUBSCRIBERS.\nPartlea who do not receive their papera. or who have any caoae of com\nplaint, will oblige The Bonania by notifying thla office.\nAll legal adverUeementa will be charged for at the rate of 12.00 per\nquare for the flrat Inaertion. There will be no exception to thi rate. No\naffidavit of publication will be made until the advertisement la paid for.\nNo .ivrtilne out. one Inch aauare or smaller will be accepted unleaa\nmade of metal. No wood baae cuta thla alae will be uaed. Wood outa are\ndangeroua to forma and presa.\nEntered at the poatofflc In Tonopah aa aecond-claaa matter.\nin not a ghost of a show tor that party remaining in power to\n.liiiK Mcb longer to the shadow of authority.\nBy siding with arranza l u. le Sam expresses faith in the\nfuture uVvelopint-iit of our southern neighbor through a speedy\nrestoration of pem-f and also keenly seents a renewal of eom\nmereial relations that have beeu sapped by the inroads of British.\nGerman and Japanese agents.\nWith Carrauza. or men of his selection, in power, it implies\nthat the Mexiran people will be informed correctly of the attitude\nof the I'nited States and thus give an object lesson on the merits\nof constitutional government instead of government by a rabble.\nTrade will revive. Amerii-au miners will hasten back to their de\nserted properties, snii'ltcrs will reopen, railroads will resume op\neration and business will begin to thrive until it strides forward\nwith as vigorous steps as it did before the removal of Diaz\nMexico is all right if it is made all right, and the laws are\nadministered with a firm hand free from the diets tM of oil mag\nnates or concessionaries who have no more lofty aspiration than\ntheir own aggrandizement.\nA truce to all further hostilities will enable that vexed country\nto get ready for the opening of the I'anama i-aiial. by rebuilding\nrailroads, erecting doeks. dredging deeper harbors and upbuilding\na merchant marine. All these reforms spell intense activity in all\nindustrial branches and the renewal of amicable relations with the\nI'nited States implies that this country will also reap a bountiful\nharvest.\nCONSOLIDATED AUTO COMPANY.\nCarrying United States mall and\nexpress makes daily trips from Tono\npah to Manhattan and Round Moun\ntain. Cars leave Tonopah daily on\narrival of mail and leave Manhattan\nat 2:30 p. m.\nW C. HARDINQ. Agent\nA store that advertise, must ba a\ntore of value of bargains or\nthe advertising would not pay.\nEFFECT OF TONOPAH CAPITAL\nCOLORADO is rejoicing over the advent of Tonopah capital in\nthat state, with the prediction that this will lead others to\nfollow. As a matter of fact, the Tonopah Mining company is not\nthe pioneer in this field, as the Knox interests had preceded it by\nthe construction of the mill at Pearce, Ariz., after the acquisition\nof the Commonwealth mine at the same place. Then there is the\ngreat mill at Aurora, whose foundation may be traced to Tonopah\ncapital. Such ventures advertise the mine of Tonopah as they\nproclaim to the world that Tonopah is on the map and producing\nat a rate that raises Rurplus funds for investment elsewhere. In\nthis way Tonopah becomes the center of mining investments and\nconservative men will look in this direction for the latest achieve\nments in milling and mining machinery. Speaking of this new\nmovement the Engnecring and Mining Journal refers to the effect\non Colorado in the following editorial:\n\"Revival of interest in Colorado mining seems to have come\nin with the new year. Companies that heretofore operated outside\nof this stale arc securing large interests here, one being the Tonopah\nMining company. The Guggenheim interests have taken over large\nmining properties, in the Rice district, and is planning extensive\nproduction that will go to American Smelting Refining company\nsmelting plant. The representative! of exploration companies are\nscouting in many camps and have intentions of closing options on\na number ol old as well as new properties. I lie coming summer\nseason will permit the investigation of several large, low grade\ncopper and gold deposits that will prove the foundations for ex\ntensive ope rations on such scales as have been developed in other\nstates, but which have not thus far been introduced into Colorado\nLitigation has prevented the operation of many properties in the\nstate, hut there seems to be a trend toward the settlement of such\nstrife by compromises or consolidations and 1914 will undoubtedly\nwitness the resumption of production in mines that have not been\nheard of for years. Again, men in the cast and north are writing\nto friends and engineers in Colorado, making innuirv for desirable\nsmall properties, it being their desire to start private mining opera\ntions on modest scales and without special publicity. If the pro\nmoter and crook can be kept away from these sincere investors,\nthe mining industry will thrive Such camps with many little\nmines instead of a few large ones require more surveyors, assayors,\nminers, machinists, mechanics and laborers of all sorts to produce.\nThe costs per ton may be higher than in the highly organized,\nlarge scale districts, but the community exhibit more prosperity\nTherefore, if small capital is willing to accept this larger cost, the\nmining districts owe it to themselves as well as to the capitalists\nto guarantee that all transactions leading up to the beginning\nof such operations be absolutely square. Heretofore several Colo\nrado mining districts have apparently openly winked at the manner\nin which \"suckers\" have been played.\"\nRAISING THE EMBARGO\nTHE proclamation of President, Wilson raising the embargo on\narms along the Rio Grande border has called the turn on\nJapan and it does not require a lunar telescope to read between the\nlines that the cunning Nipponese had been cultivating the Huerta\nadministration for the purpose of securing a foothold on Magda\nlena bay besides other commercial concessions that would give the\nOriental standing in the neighboring republic. It would have been\nsuicidal for the United States to maintain its inimical attitude\ntoward the rebels when every other country in competition with\nAmerican manufacturers was shipping arms, ammunition and food\nsupplies to the disaffected zone.\nBy removing the troops from the, border President Wilson in\nsures to the United States a large share of the commerce that\nnaturally belongs to this nation, and some astute statesmen are\nof the conviction that the order was actuated by the underlying\nmotive of regaining prestige lost during the hostilities. The tot\ntering house of Huerta has no attractions for the future, as there\nMemphis is just indulging in a prosperity dinner Doubtless\nthis is to call attention to a return of prosperity. Tonopah doesn't\nneed to hold such dinners, because prosperity has never left us.\nIt is said that Henry Lane Wilson will restate his case in a\nbook. \"Oh, that mine enemy would write a book!\" is probably on\nthe lips of President Wilson.\nJ. Ham Lewis is getting so much notoriety in England that we\nmay expect an outbreak of jealousy from Bernard Shaw.\nFOR RENT\nThree-room house com\npletely furnished. Eure\nka St liO.OO\nFour-room house com\npletely furnished; mod\nern; Ellis St $30.00\nFour-room house, fur\nnished, South st $22.50\nFour-room house. furniBhed;\nProspect St $30 .00\nThree- room house, fur\nnished, Florence ave $20\nOne-room cabin, furnished,\nnear Midway hotel $8\nINSURANCE.\nWhen you insure with us\nyou always get prompt ad\njustment. See posters of\nTatilch Bros.' sale.\nS. R. MOORE CO. CO.\n106 South Main Street\nTONOPAH NEVADA\nA FIRM FOUNDATION\nTo build on the rock one must keep his credll absolutely un\nsullied, and he must realize that the best way to do that is by\nbuilding up a bank account.\nIt is at the bank counter that a man's credit is determined,\nand the wiBe business man makes every effort to stand well at\nhis bank.\nYou are doing good triply when you keep a good balance In the\nbank you help yourself and the community, as well as the bank.\nNEVADA FIRST NATIONAL BANK\nTONOPAH, NEVADA.\nJapan has a new island which was manufactured by the re\nearthquake. Japan is welcome to the new industry\nnt\nGeneral Villa says that he has no desire to be president f\nMexico. Perhaps he wants to he a dictator like Huerta.\nThe bomb trust in New York is getting a good deal of publicity.\nIsn't it rather dangerous to unscramble a bomb trust\n\"How much did Omar drink\" inquires Harper's Weekly\nWhy so much interest in drinks that are past\nMurphy has learned that nothing fails so successfully as I'ailu.e\nINTERESTING SIDELIGHTS\nERNEST RACKLIFF\nhas an uuto stage running from\nLUNING TO G0LDYKE\nThe roadB are excellent and\ndistance 28 miles.\nAuto can also be bad for trips\nto any point in this district.\nArrange by letter or wire.\nERNEST RACKLIFF\nLUNING, NEV.\nMMMMMMiXMMlMHMMMtM\nSEND YOUR NEXT TELEGRAM OVER\nPostal Wires\nTonopah Industry for Tonopah People\nlea.\nFoundry and Machine Works\nGENERAL FOUNDRY WORK\nCast Iron, Hard Iron, Braaa,\nBronx and Alluminum Cast\nInge.\nRepair work of all descrip\ntions. Our automobile department\nthoroughly equipped.\nCAMPBELL KELLY, Inc.\nDoes the phyHiciau who says we\nshould not eat eggB intend this for\nadvice or consolation? St. Louis\nGlobe-Democrat.\nNow that a Si. Haul minister has\ncome to the defense of Ananias, real\nestate agents everywhere are feeling\nbetter. Washington Post.\nWhy worry about good works?\nAfter a long and active career of\nusefulneBa Rev Washington Gladden\nis known 10 fame as the author of\n\"tainted money.\" Cleveland Leader\nThe Londoner who said the fog\nCOASTERS HURT\nWhile coasting down a hill in Kly\nrecently on a big sled, Mrs. P. C.\nWatt was rendered unconscious, Miss\nKstella Chamberlain was severely\nbruised and Miss Agnes Kox received\na painful cut on her left hip when\nthe sled suddenly overturned. Car\nson Appeal.\nM VI. STATEMENT\nOf the Manhattan Consolidated Ex\ntension Mining company for the year\nending December 31, 1913:\nLocation of mine, Manhattan mlntriK\ndistrict, county of Nye, state of Ne\nvada. DEBIT.\nJanuary 1, 1913, to cash on hand. None\nTo aBaesamenta collected during\n1913 None\nTo amount received from other\nsources None\nCHKDIT.\nMine expenses In year 1913 None\nGeneral expenses in year 1913 $47.60\nPaid dividends In year 1913 None\nDeficit December 31, 1913 $75.00\nR. J. OOLBURN. Sec.\nANNUAL STATEMENT\nOf the Falrvlew Klmberley Mining\ncompany for the year ending De\ncember 31, 1913:\nLocation of mine, Falrvlew mining\ndistrict, county of Churchill, state of\nNevada.\nDEBIT.\nJanuary 1, 1913. to cash on hand. None\nTo assessment collected during\nISIS None\nTo amount received from other\nsources None\nCREDIT.\nMine expenaes In year 1913 None\nGeneral expenses in year 1913 $10\nPsld dividends In year 1913 None\nBalance on hand December 31,\nI' None\nR J COLBL'RN Sec\nYour Prescription\nA prescription when handed to you by a physician becomes\nyour property. You can take ii where you wish to have II com\npounded No phyalrlan in this locality will criticise your udgmenl\nIf you bring your prescriptions to us\nOUR SERVICE\nWh